Introduction

This document analyses predator fish abundance from the Kimbe Bay video survey data set. Last edit: 30 Aug 2021 BJC

Basic data wrangling: Loads fish DOV data from both survey periods (2018 and 2019) and extracts just predator observations:

Basic abundance calculations on the predator data frame

Variables:

Modelling predator abundance (response variable) against reef type (fixed effect predictor variable), with site as a random effect:

  1. Numbers of predators (response variable): This is count data and needs to be scaled against total fish assemblage size, so could convert into a proportion (0-1) but instead well scale inside the model using offset().
  2. Reef type (predictor variable (fixed effect)): Factor with 3 levels.
  3. Site (nested random effect): 4 sites per reef type, 12 total.
  4. Numbers of fish (scaling variable): Need to scale the model to account for total fish numbers

Note: Initially thought about including survey period as a fully crossed random effect, however there are only two levels within this variable making any variance partitioning meaningless (cant have variance between 2 observations - generally considered that 5 is the minimum). In theory could include as a fixed effect, however we are not really interested in it as a predictor and want to maintain model parsimony!

- Lots of zeros so perhaps will need a ZI term in the model. These are count data so expecting Poisson or neg binom distributions to work best. - Predator abundance high on pinnacles where we exclusively recorded the large schools of pelagic/semi-pelagic fishes (in particular S. qenie). Could look at transforming or adjusting the data, treating these as outliers and excluding. However, these observations may be ecologically important and the right GLMM error-family should handle these data.

Fit models

Basic GLMM with site as random factor. Will introduce offset later on. Trialled other error families but all poor fit: Gaussian, Poisson, Gamma, Beta (on %) etc

Model formulas

# Neg binom 2 (Neg binom 1 poor fit)
pred.glmmnb <- glmmTMB(No_Preds~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=predsum, family=nbinom2())  
# ZI (on neg binom 2)
pred.glmmzi <- glmmTMB(No_Preds~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=predsum, family=nbinom2(), ziformula=~1)
# Tweedie
pred.glmmt <- glmmTMB(No_Preds~Reeftype+(1|SiteCode), data=predsum, family=tweedie())

Source code for all models trialled if required (model comparisons etc)

Validation with AIC

AIC(pred.glmmnb, pred.glmmzi, pred.glmmt)

-> NB model best and most parsimonious fit, but will check for zero inflation on that model

ZI interrogation

testZeroInflation(pred.glmmnb)

## 
##  DHARMa zero-inflation test via comparison to expected zeros with
##  simulation under H0 = fitted model
## 
## data:  simulationOutput
## ratioObsSim = 0.73892, p-value = 0.24
## alternative hypothesis: two.sided

ZI test output

data: simulationOutput ratioObsSim = 0.73892, p-value = 0.24 alternative hypothesis: two.sided -> Plot shows that we are actually getting slightly fewer zeros than expected and the output quantifies this: 74% of zeros expected (non significant)

Manual calculation of probability and/or odds of a false zero

Use plogis to transform the ZI estimate:

plogis(-21.2)= 6.2e-10 -> almost no chance that any of these zeros are false exp(-21.2) -> and corresponding almost no odds that any zeros false either

-> So emmeans suggest that pinnacles have more predators than both offshore emergent and near shore reefs, but that this is highly variable. What about if we take into account overall numbers of fishes?

Model tweaking

Now going to add the offset (against total numers of fishes in assemblage) On log() scale as that is the link scale

pred.glmmnboff <- update(pred.glmmnb, ~ . + offset(log(No_Fish)))

Revalidation with AIC

AIC(pred.glmmnb,  pred.glmmnboff)

-> Improved fit for offset model

Check summary

Results (emmeans and contrasts on response scale - numbers of predators)

# R2 if you want but not very useful for glmm

# emmeans and contrasts first
abuncontrasts <- emmeans(pred.glmmnboff, pairwise ~ Reeftype, transform='response', combine=TRUE) %>%
  confint() %>% 
  as.data.frame() 

# pvalues
abunpvals <- emmeans(pred.glmmnboff,  ~ Reeftype, transform='response', combine=TRUE) %>% 
  pairs() %>% 
  as.data.frame() 
  
# Combine for full results table
abunresults <- bind_cols(abuncontrasts, abunpvals[5:6]) 

# Write to csv
write_csv(abunresults, file = "../../output/rtables/abunresults.csv")

  tab_df(file="../../output/rtables/abunresults.html", title = "Abundance contrasts (estimates)") #%>%
